      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Anthony Walton White Evans (1817-1886) was an American civil engineer.  A graduate of Rensselaer Polytechnicm he served as assistant engineer on the Erie Canal, assistant on the construction of a branch of the New York and Harlem Railroad, and chief engineer for construction of railroads in Chile and Peru.   Upon returning to the United States in 1860 he became a successful consulting engineer and later president of the United States Petroleum Company and the Spuyten Duyvil Rolling Mill.</p><p>The Montezuma swamp later became the Montezuma National Wildlife Refuge, a major resting area for waterfowl and other waterbirds on their journeys to and from nesting areas in northeastern and east-central Canada.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Anthony Walton White Evans Correspondence</emph> consists of a letter from civil engineer Anthony Walton White Evans to William Paterson, describing his work surveying the Montezuma and Cayuga swamps in central New York.   The letter reads, in part:</p><blockquote><p>I believe I told you in my last that the state had ordered our party to make a survey of the Montezuma and Cauga [Cayuga] marshes.  Now this same survey is by far the worst and most laborious job that the states have in their gift.</p></blockquote>
      </scopecontent>
      
